   "abstract": "Kimberle Crenshaw argues that violence against women of color cannot be understood by looking at race or gender one at a time, because the women hit hardest sit at the intersection of both systems and fall through the gaps of single-axis analysis. A cornerstone of critical race theory, the essay names intersectionality as the move of analysing harm where systems of identity and power overlap. The course uses it as the lens for asking not only how race shapes technology, but how race, gender, and class shape it together.",
   "coreIdea": "Harm is clearest at the intersection of systems; an analysis that looks at one axis at a time misses the people hit hardest.",
